# Fleet Doctrine & Combat Logic

**Canonical source:** `Universe/fleet_doctrine_and_combat_logic.md`

Reference this document before writing or editing any battle scene. Systems rules layer — not narrative content.

**Also load:** `Universe/canon_and_world_rules.md` for vessel class specifications.

## Core principle

Combat is determined by **role advantage**, **fleet composition**, and **positioning/initiative** — not raw firepower, size, or tech alone.

## Warfare layers

| Layer | Classes | Function |
|-------|---------|----------|
| Light | Fighters, Ion Fighters, Corvettes | Harassment, screening, swarm pressure |
| Line | Frigates, Cruisers | Engagement line; missiles vs capital; plasma vs frigates |
| Capital | Heavy Cruisers, Battleships | Fleet anchors; HC flexible vs mixed fleets; BB weak vs fighters alone |
| Strategic | Dreadnaughts, Titans, Leviathans, Fleet Carriers | Zone control; smaller fleets react, not engage head-on |

## Combat behavior (summary)

- **Rule A:** Ships win by role deployment, not size
- **Rule B:** Capital ships require fighter screen, sensors, coordination
- **Rule C:** Fighters are force multipliers, not war-winners alone
- **Rule D:** Targeting data is a weapon
- **Rule E:** Range favors corvettes/fighters (close), cruisers (mid), dreadnaughts+ (long)

## Battle outcomes

Must reflect composition, positioning, information, coordination, and attrition — never single-ship superiority or tonnage logic.

## Kestrel Veil

Scout-Class — **not** combat dominant. Survives via speed, evasion, environment, crew ingenuity, enemy miscalculation. Doctrine-breaking outcomes under stress, not hidden battleship capability.

